      <tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>10 threads, <a href=/journal2.html?user=93075&start=0>1</a>  page(s) long</td><td  style='font-size: 9.5px;' align=right>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></form><ul>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f10736730603821>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=10736730603821>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=10736730603821>Back From The Dead</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=10736730603821#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Fri, Jan 9th 1:32 PM 2004</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93075><span id=Scholar>Ynar</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>32 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.20]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>It's been a long time since I posted to my journal. In December of 2002 I was part of a layoff and had to send my PC back to the company (I'm a Mac guy most of the time), so I had no computer on which to play EQ and no cash with which to buy a PC.<br><br>Fast forward to last October. A consulting gig finally came through that required me to build a PC for myself. With some hesitation, I purchased EQ Evolutions and the Lost Dungeons of Norrath expansions. I wasn't sure if I really would play as much, but wanted to say hello to all my old friends on Zebuxoruk.<br><br>Ah, who was I kidding? I'm as addicted as ever - maybe even more so. Sony has added some really nice features to the game and LDoN is a lot of fun. When I left Ynar he was level 52. Within six weeks I had him at 55. He's now 57. For those of you laughing at my advancement rate, I should remind you that it took me nearly a year to reach level 36. I do a lot of questing and trade skills (damn you prayer shawl quests!) so I haven't concentrated on leveling as much as some do.<br><br>I even started my epic quest a few days ago. I may never finish it, but it's been fun so far. While the necromancer epic item isn't that great, the process is certainly entertaining. My biggest quandry now is whether or not I want to find a guild. I never took a last name, and I roleplay a lot. I like being the mysterious loner necromancer wandering the lands.<br><br>Still, there are things I'll never see without a guild, so I know I'll eventually need to find one. As I start grouping with more and more high level characters, I'm learning which of the guilds are militant and which are fun. I'll never join a guild that conducts mandatory raids - EQ is a game: it's what I do to relieve stress, not cause it.<br><br>It's good to be back from the dead. And it's still good to be a necro. =-)</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>-- Bene Moriore</td></tr>
	     <tr><td colspan=2 align=right class=mform id=fs8>0 Replies</td></tr>
	     </form></table>
<tr><td colspan=2><ul>
</ul></td></tr></table>

<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f103611924563376>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=103611924563376>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=103611924563376>Egotistical Necromancers and Sony's Lost Cigar.</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=103611924563376#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Thu, Oct 31st 10:14 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93075><span id=Scholar>Ynar</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>32 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.31]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Well, it's been awhile since I posted here - a combination of another burnout and my newfound affinity for a few message boards. But I'm back, and this one might be a doozy. as I wait for the Halloween festivities to begin - both online and at my front door. <br><br>So sit back, grab your favorite beverage and enjoy the rantish stylings of Ynar...<br><br>First off, wow! Responses! I didn't think anyone would ever respond. Thank you to both of you. Phreda, there's not much chance of me going the fiction route now... heh heh.<br><br>Kythian, thanks very much for your comments. Regarding the relative egotism of necromancers, well, I certainly can't disagree with you. I've found (especially since discovering the necro.eqclasses.com board and the serverwide necromancer channel) that there are indeed quite a few necromancers who have a superiority complex. The question in my mind is, did they become that way because of the powers of the necromancer, or did they choose the necromancer as a class because it matched their own real-life persona?<br><br>To be sure, Necromancers are a powerful class. Even after years of nerfing with little compensation (things have gotten better over the last 6 months or so), there are few things that necromancers can't do. Interestingly, while druids and shadow knights are examples of the official &quot;hybrid&quot; class, it's my opinion that necromancers actually fit that description a little more closely.<br><br>While we don't have the melee or armor skills, we do have such a wide variety of abilities that it's possible to fill many roles. Unfortunately, that versatility comes with a price - the classic &quot;jack of all trades, master of none&quot; dilemma.<br><br>Still, that doesn't stop a few (well, maybe more than a few) abrasive necromancers from giving the entire class a reputed black eye. Add to that the relatively low number of necromancers (the last statistic I saw put us as the second lowest played class) and the chance that you're going to come across a &quot;jerkromancer&quot; is pretty high.<br><br>Some of the necromancer community exhibits some definite minority group behavioral traits - an inherent defensivenes, paranoia, and an overwhelming willingness to help our own at the expense of others. I've watched necromancers sit and do nothing while someone yelled for help 30 feet away, and I've seen necromancers drop everything they're doing to help another necromancer on the other side of the world...<br><br>Still - is this an inherent class trait? Does playing a necromancer produce these behaviors? Logically, no... there are two types of characters in EQ - those that are a complete fantasy for the player... a role that they would never assume in real life (the dashing hero, the evil sorcerer, a male, a female). Then there are those whose characters are mostly an extension of themselves. I certainly fall into the latter category. Even when I'm roleplaying, my outlook is that Ynar is not evil, he's just fascinated with learning as much as he can and found reanimation of the dead interesting.<br><br>And I try to help others whenever I can, whether roleplaying or not - but that's because I like to help others in the game.<br><br>So perhaps I should amend my earlier post about grouping with necromancers to say this:<br><br>Don't be afraid to invite a necromancer into your group, and be sure to give him or her a chance to learn your group's dynamics and style. But don't be afraid to kick a necromancer (or any player for that matter) who is rude, does things that endanger the group, or acts like a cowboy. I've kicked necromancers for those things in my own groups.<br><br>BUT - if you find a good necromancer, cherish them, love them, and invite them to group and raid often. Yes, we are a solo class, and many of us chose the class because we didn't have time to properly play a &quot;group only&quot; class, but the truly talented necromancer will always be a boon to your success. and appreciates all the nice attention. and the chance to get some additional lewt that we can't get by ourselves.<br><br><b>The Everquest Atlas</b><br>For those of you who don't know, Sony has released the Everquest Atlas, an attractive, full color, spiral bound book of nearly 600 pages. The back of the box glowingly says that the &quot;rich and mysterious world of EverQuest is opened to players in a full-color book that uncovers the wonders of Norrath in fantastic detail.&quot;<br><br>It goes on to say that it includes &quot;over 170 full-color maps - which include the forthcoming EverQuest: The Planes of Power expansion.&quot;<br><br>Now, I'm a huge fan of Muse and the www.eqatlas.com site. It's helped me through many a zone and to avoid many a death. But I thought I'd take the chance on this $19.95 tome of maps because it would be nice to have a book next to the computer instead of looking back and forth from one computer to the other, and the book promised to have some maps that I can't currently get from eqatlas.com.<br><br>Make no mistake, this book is gorgeous! It's just the right size to have next to the keyboard, spiral bound so it lays flat, satisfyingly heavy, and attractively laid out. The &quot;laser&quot; style cover is pretty cool as well.<br><br>And that's about it.<br><br>While I can't say that it was a complete waste of money, I can say that this is definitely a &quot;Close, but no cigar&quot; product. It had enormous potential to be a fantastic reference and guide, but falls just short of the mark.<br><br>Let me illustrate a few of the shortcomings of the book.<br><br>1. No coordinates. Maps are a representative form of design - they are most often a two dimensional representation of a three dimensional space, and are an extrordinarily rich form of information/communication. The most basic function of a map is to show you where things are in relation to each other. The book's maps do this. But without coordinates, you have to identify where you are in the first place... not always the easiest task. Not an insurmountable problem, but a coordinate grid would have made this book <b>much</b> more useful.<br><br>2. Weird perspective. All of the maps are drawn in 3/4 perspective. While making for a pretty drawing, it does make doing things like... oh... adding coordinates a little bit harder. To make things more difficult, North is often not &quot;up&quot; on the page. This is sometimes a necessary evil when a zone is much wider than it is tall (like the Plane of Knowledge), but when North is always changing, it makes it just a tad slower to get oriented. Again, not a huge problem, but sometimes annoying.<br><br>3. Limited information. This is one of the big, fat, glaring problems with the book. As an example, the map for North Freeport gives a whopping 5 locations: The zone line, the Temple of Marr, the hall of Truth, The bank, and the bard's guild. That's it. No merchant information, no NPC locations, etc. The timorous deep description mentions the raptors, but doesn't give you any clue where they might be located.<br><br>4. Incorrect information. My only example of this so far is that the Dreadlands description shows the monster level as being 1-10. This is most likely just an unfortunate, isolated typo, but if Sony is going to promote this book as being worth the price because you're getting information straight from the source, they darn well better make sure that the information is accurate...<br><br>5. The planes. This is perhaps my biggest gripe with the book. There are only two or three maps of the planes. The plane of Knowledge is fairly well mapped, but it's already in the PoP expansion manual. There are one or two rough maps (Innovation, Tranquility), but for the most part, the Planes are represented by some artwork - a guilliotene for Justice, a shipwrecked coast for Storms, and some that might be maps, but not having been there, I can't tell for sure. They sure don't feel like maps in any case.<br><br>Now I know what you're saying... &quot;Ynar, Sony wants people to explore the Planes and discover the unknown.&quot; Fine. I have no problem with that. Until you recall the back of the box that you can read through the shrinkwrap: &quot;over 170 maps - which include the forthcoming Everquest: The Planes of Power expansion.&quot;<br><br>Misleading at best.<br><br>And quite frankly, the planes maps were the primary reason for my deciding to pony up twenty bucks for the book, since there seems to be some political brouhaha or snubbing going on between Sony and Muse over at eqatlas.com (according to his site, he wasn't invited to beta test the PoP expansion and leaves it to the reader to figure out why that might be). If eqatlas wasn't going to have the maps, the book would be a big help.<br><br>Also, if Sony really wants me to explore and discover everything on my own, why did they publish an atlas?<br><br>So knowing that Muse wasn't likely to have maps of the planes any time soon, and seeing that the box advertised maps of the planes, I bought the hype. Caveat Emptor, baby.<br><br>So what does the book do right? Well, there's some really nice descriptive text that not only gives you an indication (albeit sometimes a vague indication) of what to expect from a zone. Much of the lore and backstory is provided, and it's fun to read.<br><br>In addition, there are &quot;maps&quot; of zones that aren't readily available on the main EQ sites that I visit (e.g. eqatlas.com). And did I mention that the artwork is really pretty?<br><br>But essentially, what Sony has published is the book that should have been in the box. I recognize that Sony doesn't want to provide spoiler information, but representing this product as an atlas that &quot;uncovers the wonders of Norrath in fantastic detail&quot; is *really* stretching it.<br><br>When I bought the Prima guides, I figured out that I had really just paid $20 for information that was already available on the internet and that should have been in the user manual. But ok, now I have it all in one place and in an easy to use form, and this seems to have become the standard practice in the software gaming industry - publish a crappy, bare bones instruction manual, and rake in another $20 with a misnamed &quot;strategy guide.&quot; (But that's another rant. :) )<br><br>In the case of this atlas, however, the information isn't even as good as what's on the internet. Close, but no cigar.<br><br>So my bottom line recommendation is this: take that $20 and buy yourself a a few more months of Allakhazam premium service and send the rest to Muse via paypal. He's giving you a lot better value and information and can use the money a lot more than Sony.<br><br>If however, you're a completist and really want a &quot;keepsake&quot; type item with lore, nice descriptive text, illustratons, screenshots, etc. the Everquest Atlas from Sony isn't a horrible purchase - it just isn't what it says it is.<br><br>Well, by now your coffee is cold and my fingers are numb. The trick-or-treaters have stopped ringing my doorbell and the porch light is off, so it's off to Norrath I go to try and grab some phat halloween lewt! And probably to die a few times.<br><br>Safe journeying and journaling!<br><br>Ynar - Heretic of Zebuxoruk<br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Nov&nbsp;&nbsp;1 00:01:32 2002</em></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>-- Bene Moriore</td></tr>
