	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=173871><span id=Scholar>kythian</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>93 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Greetings Master Ynar!<br><br>I have just read through all your posts, and firstly I would like to say it was rather pleasant reading. Your style is tight, and to the point... not to mention clear. So few people have the proper talent to fully express their opinions in writing. In this category you shine.<br><br>Now, for some reponses to your previous posts.<br><br><br>On Coin Dropping, Burnout and Rediscovery<br><br>I agree with you completely that the coin-dropping issue was heavy-handed. I know of many monks (in particular) and low-strength classes (in general) that often dropped piles of coins to lighten their load. Personally, I've always destroyed my coins, but that's a personal preference stemming from an abhorance to littering. After all, my main character is a druid. *Grin*<br><br>On burnout, I can say that I have been there many times myself. I am a veteran player (though I hope not a snobby one), having played since the original release and even knowing one of the original beta testers. So my exposure to EQ started long before I activated my account. There have been many times throughout the years that I have simply walked away, most recently for over two months. I eventually gravitate back and start playing again, but it comes and goes. Rather, &quot;I&quot; come and go. Suffice it to say, it's not so much the game that brings me back, but the odd companionship.<br><br><br>Legends - Timeless or Moldy?<br><br>I agree that $40 per month is entirely too much to pay for something that we should have had since the begining. The only real thing I can add to your comments on the matter is that with the release of Anarchy Online, Dark Ages of Camelot and the others peeking over the horizon, Verant will be taking a serious look at the way things operate. If they don't, they'll tank. In fact, the primary reasoning for getting rid of the spellbook while meditating (at least, presumably) is due to the influence of DAoC.<br><br>So long as Verant continues to provide these subtle improvements, and stears clear of any more heavy-handed &quot;fixes&quot;, EQ will continue to thrive.<br><br><br>If you've never grouped with a necro...<br><br>In fact I have. On several occasions. And this is what I have discovered. (Please feel free to comment on this one as you see fit.)<br><br>In general, necromancers are cocky. Sometimes even arrogant. But, admitedly, not without some cause.<br><br>Necromancers are very powerful. They can solo as well as anyone, if not better. They have a wide array of powers available to help them handle (quite frankly) ANY situation. This is good. And bad. Many of the necros that I have encountered in the game have swollen egos (I don't know if this is a pre-existing condition, or something that happens when the player selects the necro upon log in, but it's very consistent) and have no qualms about letting everyone know.<br><br>On the other hand, there have been a few exceptional ones. These ones are a scream (no pun intended) to group with! They nearly as versitile as a bard. Sometimes better! Have you ever seen a druid and a necromancer paired up? You have never seen such a frightening sight.<br><br>Chloroplast (or Regenerate, at lower levels) on the Necro, one of the various Thorn spells on the pet, Skin Like Nature (at level 49 and up) on the Necro AND pet! SoW, heals (big enough to keep a necro alive, if not a warrior), DoT's that stack with each other (gotta love Breath of Ro and Splurt working together!), the nightmare goes on!<br><br>All in all, I avoid necromancers. But when I find a good one, the experience, loot, and most important, the fun just roll in.<br><br><br>I don't really have anything constructive to add to the two most recent posts, so I'll conclude with this: Keep posting. I find your arguements well constructed and intriguing (sp?). Very thought provoking.<br><br>Cheers!<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Thu Jul 11 13:08:41 2002</em></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>"Walk in the light, and you will be seen. Walk in the dark, and you will surely stumble over the <i>un</i>seen."</td></tr>
