	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93075><span id=Scholar>Ynar</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>32 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Today, I got an email from Sony offering me a free 30 day trial on an additional account. It said that I could use it myself or give the code to a friend and that they granted permission to copy my media to do so.<br><br>But this paragraph kind of surprised me:<br><br>&quot;Open up new solo gameplay possibilities you've only dreamed about. Got two computers? Use the free account key provided in this email and your existing software to start a second account and play two characters together -- at the same time! How cool would it be to build a cleric or druid of your own and have them at your fingertips for buffs, healing and more? &quot;<br><br>So the message Sony is sending me is this: &quot;We think twinking is bad and we'll do quite a bit to make it harder for you... unless of course you pay us more money in which case we think twinking is great, and we'll even throw in a free 30 day trial to help you out.&quot;<br><br>I'm not in my normal verbose mood, so all I'll say is wow. And I thought some of the players I met in EQ were mercenary (like the cleric who decides what % exp rez you get based on how much money you promise him) but this takes the cake. Good job, Sony.</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>-- Bene Moriore</td></tr>
