<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f10147401244779>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=10147401244779>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=10147401244779>If you've never grouped with a necro...</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=10147401244779#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Feb 26th 11:16 AM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93075><span id=Scholar>Releaux</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>32 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.50]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Necromancers. Great solo class, but pretty sucky in a group, right?<br><br>I don't think so.<br><br>I've found during my time in Norrath that Necromancers are frequently underestimated and misunderstood. I thought I'd take advantage of this downtime (there appears to have been a meltdown after today's patch) to outline some of the things that necromancers can do that you might not be aware of.<br><br>There are some obvious ones: tracking or summoning corpses, curing rabies and other diseases (we work with the undead a lot so we have to be able to cure all the lovely things they carry), and a full line of spells that affect the undead (damage, root, charm, etc.) But there are several necromancer abilities that almost always evoke a &quot;You can do THAT?&quot; from groups I'm in...<br><br>(Note that I'm only at level 33, so there are even more things available at higher levels, but if you're a high level, you've probably learned about necromancers already. =-)<br><br>Pets<br>====<br>The most obvious sign of the necromancer is the little skeleton buddy following him around. This might seem obvious, but many people forget that this pet is another pair of hands beating on a mob. Even better, a pet only takes 1% of the experience in a group no matter how much damage it does. You probably don't want a necro pet tanking regularly, but it's a great assistant damage dealer.<br><br>Think of a necro and his pet as a melee/caster combination. Higher level necro pets are actually different classes. Later necro pets can be necros (with lifetap) rogues (with backstab) or monks (with a flying kick). <br><br><br>Healer<br>======<br>At lower levels, a necromancer can make a pretty effective healer with the pact line of spells, especially as backup healer. Sure it might be kind of spooky to know that the necro is draining her own blood to give you HP, but do you really want to refuse the help? From level 30 until 44, this becomes less and less powerful, but it might be enough to keep you from dying from a DOT...<br><br><br>Snare<br>=====<br>The darkness line of spells give necromancers a great combo: snare and dot in one spell! As an example, the Level 29 Dooming Darkness spell not only slows movement by 60%, it also does up to 300 damage. That's just gravy if you're already needing to snare.<br><br><br>Root<br>====<br>We get it later than other classes, but once at level 34, a necro can root with the best of 'em.<br><br><br>Mez<br>===<br>That's right, I said mez. At level 24, we get a spell called Screaming Terror that mezzes a mob for 18 seconds. What's more, there's even a chance for an aggro memory wipe (but don't count on it). Unfortunately, a great deal of necro gear lowers charisma which can lead to resists, so don't ask a necro who's never tried mezzing to do it when you absolutely need it. A necro who's tried will know whether or not they have a dependable mez.<br><br>Remember also, that if the mez breaks early, that mob is going to be breathing down that necro's... er... neck. So be ready to taunt.<br><br><br>Feign Pulling/Splitting<br>=======================<br>Used infrequently, but still something to think about, necros can use Feign Death to pull a mob or root/feign split a spawn just like a monk. Unlike monks, however, a necro's FD is a spell (with a chance for a fizzle) so it's not as dependable as a monk.<br><br><br>The Mana Battery (&quot;Twitching the Healer&quot;)<br>=========================================<br>This is the big enchilada. At level 24, necros get a spell that will probably change their role in groups - especially in raid situations: the first in the Subversion line of spells. <br><br>I love using this spell in lower level zones on unsuspecting casters. I watch a caster fight and fight and fight, then come back to med, expecting a 5 minute wait while that mana bar slowly crawls up to full.<br><br>Then BAM! Full mana.<br><br>It does my black heart no end of good to hear &quot;WHAT WAS THAT???&quot;<br><br>The subversion line transfers mana from the necro to any targeted caster. When both are roughly equal in levels, it's about a two to one ratio (one bub of my mana will give you a half-bub). We become the clerics of mana and (not surprisingly) often end up mana-healing clerics. =-)<br><br>Here's the drill (it might sound complicated, but it really isn't). I convert my HP into mana. I give the mana to a needy caster. I then drain a mob of their HP to replenish mine. Wash, rinse, repeat.<br><br>It can sometimes be more efficient for the party healer to just heal the necro instead of counting on the necro to drain HP from a mob. My personal favorite is to get a regenerate from a shaman, then cast my mana drain spell. It's a poor man's clarity. Even better would be a real clarity, eliminating the need for HP conversion.<br><br>Pulling goes on much longer when the healer or nuker doesn't have to med as much.<br><br><br><br>So there you have it! A necromancer will never replace an enchanter for mezzing, or a monk for feigning, or a warrior for tanking, but they're a great class that can play several different roles in a group. (Plus, we're generally really nice people deep down. No, seriously. I mean it. Quit laughing.)<br></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>-- Bene Moriore</td></tr>
