<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f101232988634603>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=101232988634603>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=101232988634603>Burning Out and Rediscovery</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=101232988634603#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Jan 29th 2:46 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93075><span id=Scholar>Releaux</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>32 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.50]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Well, my journal isn't turning out as what I had originally intended it to be. I had originally planned for a more role-play oriented character journal for my primary (Ynar, Level 31 Necromancer on Zebuxoruk). I'd always wanted to try my hand at some fiction writing, and this seemed like an easy introduction.<br><br>However, I find myself being more interested in talking about the Everquest experience than in documenting what Ynar does in-game. More than likely, you play the game too, and have seen much of what I would describe.<br><br>Instead, today I'll recount my recent departure from and subsequent return to Norrath.<br><br>It all happened around Halloween. The GM events were in full force and I, like so many others, was rabidly in pursuit of nice goodies. This was the beginning of the end. I saw greed turn so many (ordinarily nice) people into lewt-grubbing jerks, that the events stopped being fun.<br><br>Then they just wouldn't stop! I expected maybe a day or two... but a week? I started cheering for the people who were going after the NPCs that would end an event. I sympathized with the people who didn't get that special trinket (I never did get that nice cloak), but I was ready to get back to normal EQ life. I was in the middle of my first hell level, and getting experience was next to impossible with most people swarming the event zones all the time.<br><br>Then came *the patch.* If you've read my first journal entry, you already know how I feel about the coin drop issue and there's no point in recounting it here. Suffice to say, however, that this was more or less the final straw. I was officially burned out.<br><br>I rediscovered real life. I watched TV. I got remotivated on some particularly dull projects at work. I traveled and visited family without wishing I was playing EQ. It was refreshing.<br><br>Just after Thanksgiving, I got an email from the folks at Anarchy Online. I had purchased the game in the summer, but cancelled my account because it was just too buggy and slow. The email said that they had made lots of improvements and invited me to try the game again for another 30 days at no charge. This is the kind of customer service and attention that I wish Verant would exhibit more often.<br><br>So I played AO for a few weeks. Not nearly as hard as I had played EQ, but I enjoyed the experience. Ultimately, I just didn't get into AO as much as EQ, but I think it's definitely a viable game now. I didn't continue my account at the end of the trial period, though.<br><br>During the holiday break I tried logging back into EQ a couple of times, but just never felt like doing anything. I was afraid that my burnout was permanent.<br><br>But one day a few weeks ago, out of the blue - I felt like playing. Maybe I just needed some time to decompress - I'm certainly not as serious as I used to be about the game, and if I miss a night of playing, I don't begrudge whatever it is that I'm doing instead. <br><br>I wish I could level more quickly, but Verant seems intent to keep the game artificially long, so I'm not as worried about it as I used to be. I'm still ticked off about the coin dropping thing, though.<br><br>Ultimately, I enjoy EQ a lot. It's a wonderful world to explore, and that's what I'm doing more of these days. Now I'm more interested in leveling up so I can see some of the zones I've never been to. I do have to admit, however, that it's a really nice, somewhat guilty pleasure to go back and stomp on some NPC or Mob that made your life a living hell in the early days (Phaeril Nightshire, I'm looking in your direction). I'm currently exploring the Ocean of Tears. It's an interesting zone, and I'm one skill point away from being a master swimmer.<br><br>So while this isn't new or earth shattering advice - take a break every now and then. You'll end up appreciating the game even more!</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>-- Bene Moriore</td></tr>
