<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f100533308215654>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=100533308215654>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=100533308215654>Coin Dropping.</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93075&mid=100533308215654#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Fri, Nov 9th 2:11 PM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93075><span id=Scholar>Releaux</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>32 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [3.50]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>This may be a dubious beginning to my journal, but since Verant decided to bury my post on the subject and not let others hear my argument, I have to post it here.<br><br>As part of this week's patch, Verant finally bowed to the desires of the majority of its customers and removed the heinous Trivial Loot Code (or "Anti-Bottom-Feeding" code as some like to call it) from The Warrens and Stonebrunt Mountains. I applaud them for this.<br><br>The TLC was a reaction to a problem that can definitely be frustrating for many young characters - farming by high levels in low level zones. Unfortunately, the solution provided was indicative of a fundamental disagreement I've developed with Verant's game administration philosophy: a seemingly arbitrary and arrogant willingness to limit the enjoyment of a majority of its customers based on the preferences of its game design staff.<br><br>In a nutshell, my argument is this: It is not Verant's place to tell me how I will best enjoy the game.<br><br>Now don't get me wrong, this is Verant's product, and they are free to make it behave in any manner they see fit. But please don't try to tell me that it's "more realistic" that the Kobold King in The Warrens would magically not be carrying an item simply because he was killed by a stronger person... Verant continued to try and justify the TLC by saying that "a real high level character wouldn't have time to do these things himself and would get lower level characters to do menial tasks." This is exactly the kind of attitude that makes me the most angry.<br><br>My character doesn't *trust* underlings to do the job. (And on a side note, I enjoy collecting my own bone chips... sometimes you need a break from the adventure). But with TLC, Verant was *forcing* me into a role that I didn't want to play.<br><br>But happily, Verant has decided to do away with TLC because it was so overwhelmingly disliked.<br><br>Unfortunately, Verant has given with the right hand and taken with the left, because in the very same patch, we lost the ability to drop coin.<br><br>This is ludicrous. Once again, Verant has chosen the most heavy-handed method possible to address a relatively minor problem - the potential for new characters to be scammed into dropping their coin.<br><br>Now the easiest and least intrusive solution to this problem would have been for Verant to simply add the confirmation dialog box present when you try to drop an item on the ground. Instead, because they "couldn't see any valid reason" to drop coin, they removed the ability entirely.<br><br>Instead of providing us with an option, they forced a behavior on us. I am no longer able to anonymously drop coin in newbie gardens. As a player, I like to help other characters. As a Necromancer, it isn't in my character to give coin to a halfling. Now I have to make a choice... either compromise my character and come up with some rationalization to fit Verant's preference, or just not help other players any more.<br><br>Then there is the whole twinking issue. Now I don't really twink my alternate characters, but to be honest, I hate the process of getting from level 1 to the mid-teens. I've done it once, and I don't really have any desire to do it again. More to the point, it's not Verant's place to tell me that I *should* enjoy it. Before the coin drop nerf, if I wanted to play through those levels, I could, and if I didn't want to, well it wasn't difficult to provide some coin to the new toon to get past those levels as quickly as possible.<br><br>(Yes, I can still trade coin between toons by using a 3rd party, but I either risk the coin with someone I don't know, or inconvienence one of my friends).<br><br>Verant's additional justification was that they were having a great deal of customer support traffic with people who had inadvertantly dropped coin and wanted it back, in spite of the stated policy that a GM *will not* restore coin or items.<br><br>I say that they'll just trade one support issue for another as people who lose coin in bad twinking decisions make exactly the same petitions.<br><br>It's my belief that Verant wanted to make twinking more difficult and found a way to do it without looking like they were doing it directly. It's pretty obvious, however, that they went out of their way to avoid the obvious solution that would have the least impact on people (confirmation box) and went with the ham-fisted "you will do what we want" approach that is becoming increasingly less tolerable with each new instance.<br><br>Verant has done an amazing job creating a fabulous world that I am absolutely hooked on. But it has developed an attitude that it can tell me how I'll best enjoy the game, and I don't appreciate that one bit. For a long time, it has been able to force that attitude on its customer base because it was far and away the best MMORPG in the world. That's going to change in the next year or two, and Verant needs to reevaluate its position or risk&nbsp;&nbsp;alienating its customer base.<br><br>Verant, you can tell me the rules of the world you've created, you can even change the rules on a whim, but please quit trying to rationalize your preferences by telling me that I will enjoy the game more with your new restrictions. You don't know how I most enjoy the game.<br><br>Twinking and leaving coins for other players didn't hurt anyone else, and most likely caused the people doing those things to enjoy themselves. Removing coin dropping annoys most of us and makes the game less enjoyable.</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>-- Bene Moriore</td></tr>
